    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start, but it's a bit too polished. Sterling is a bit more hardened than that. Can you expand on the part where he talks about the tribes themselves? I want him to describe the contrast between the 'ordered' world the crew comes from and the 'chaos' of the people they are encountering. Make it more descriptive of their lack of structure or their 'wild' nature to really show why the crew feels they need to step in and establish order.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Men of the ‘British Empire,’ I stand before you, bruised by wilderness, determined; for the raw, boundless chaos that lies ahead, a stark contrast to our very own London streets, our meticulously organized society—we carry the torch of civilization to the darkness, to this untamed Congo. Behold these earth-shrinkers—savages, I am called, and for a fleeting moment, such is the parlance I find myself speaking, parroting what lies uncomfortably comfortably within the confines of our every duty to 'uplift.'\n\nThese people, they dwell without the hourglass of our impeccable timekeeping, without the compass of our science to guide their every step. Their 'societies' operate on the rhythms of the sun and moon, ungrounded and ungoverned—starless odysseys through the night sky, absent of empirical light and the beacon of salt of our experiences.\n\nWe, bearing the storied chronicles of English discipline, venture forth to be their undertakers and architects—imparting structure where none exists, sowing seeds of governance in infertile soils hardened by civil disarray. It is our charge, our unquestionable responsibility, to bring forth the radiance of civility",
      "source": "target",
